# Wholesale Customers Dataset – Detailed Description

## Overview
The **Wholesale Customers Dataset** contains information about annual spending by wholesale customers on different product categories.  
The dataset is widely used for **customer segmentation**, **clustering**, and **market analysis** tasks in machine learning.

The data represents spending behavior of customers belonging to different **regions** and **distribution channels**. Businesses can use this information to identify purchasing patterns, understand customer groups, and design targeted marketing strategies.

---

## Source
The dataset is publicly available from the **UCI Machine Learning Repository**.

Dataset name: **Wholesale Customers Dataset**

Number of observations: **440 customers**

Number of variables: **8 features**

---

## Dataset Structure

Each row in the dataset represents a **single wholesale customer**.

Each column represents the **annual spending amount (monetary units)** on a specific product category.

| Feature | Data Type | Description |
|-------|-----------|-------------|
| Channel | Categorical | Distribution channel of the customer |
| Region | Categorical | Geographic region of the customer |
| Fresh | Numeric | Annual spending on fresh products |
| Milk | Numeric | Annual spending on milk products |
| Grocery | Numeric | Annual spending on grocery products |
| Frozen | Numeric | Annual spending on frozen products |
| Detergents_Paper | Numeric | Annual spending on detergents and paper products |
| Delicatessen | Numeric | Annual spending on delicatessen products |

---

## Feature Description

### Channel
Represents the type of distribution channel used by the customer.

Possible values:

| Value | Channel Type |
|------|-------------|
| 1 | Horeca (Hotel/Restaurant/Cafe) |
| 2 | Retail |

This variable helps differentiate **food service businesses** from **retail stores**.

---

### Region
Represents the geographic region where the customer operates.

Possible values:

| Value | Region |
|------|-------|
| 1 | Lisbon |
| 2 | Oporto |
| 3 | Other Region |

This variable allows analysis of **regional purchasing behavior**.

---

### Fresh
Annual spending on fresh products.

Examples of fresh products include:

- Fruits
- Vegetables
- Fresh meat
- Seafood

Businesses such as restaurants typically spend heavily in this category.

---

### Milk
Annual spending on milk-based products.

Examples include:

- Milk
- Cheese
- Yogurt
- Dairy products

Retail grocery stores may have significant spending in this category.

---

### Grocery
Annual spending on grocery products.

Examples include:

- Packaged food
- Dry food products
- Canned goods
- Household groceries

This category often shows strong correlation with **Detergents_Paper**.

---

### Frozen
Annual spending on frozen food products.

Examples include:

- Frozen vegetables
- Frozen meat
- Frozen ready-to-eat meals

Customers with storage facilities may spend more in this category.

---

### Detergents_Paper
Annual spending on detergents and paper products.

Examples include:

- Cleaning detergents
- Paper towels
- Tissue products
- Cleaning supplies

Retail stores usually have high spending in this category.

---

### Delicatessen
Annual spending on delicatessen items.

Examples include:

- Prepared foods
- Specialty meats
- Gourmet products

These products are often sold in specialty stores or premium food outlets.

---

## Data Characteristics

Some important characteristics of the dataset include:

- Spending values vary widely across customers.
- The dataset contains **skewed distributions**, meaning a small number of customers have very high spending.
- Certain features are **strongly correlated**, especially:
  - Grocery
  - Detergents_Paper
  - Milk

Because of these characteristics, preprocessing steps such as **scaling and outlier detection** are important before applying machine learning algorithms.

---

## Typical Use Cases

This dataset is commonly used in data science and machine learning for:

### Customer Segmentation
Grouping customers based on purchasing behavior.

### Market Basket Analysis
Understanding product purchasing patterns.

### Retail Analytics
Studying sales distribution across product categories.

### Unsupervised Learning
Applying clustering algorithms such as:

- K-Means Clustering
- Hierarchical Clustering
- DBSCAN

### Feature Analysis
Studying correlations between product categories.
